@node freeware "Freeware Notice"

Freeware notice
================

  Keeper is freeware. Keeper and its accompanying files may be distributed
freely by any means as long as the archive remains intact and unchanged.
Keeper may not be sold in any form, although a resonable copying fee is
acceptable.

  Keeper is my first real Amiga application. I have made it freeware
because I felt I owed to the Amiga community what I enjoyed from it. I
hope this program will be useful and helpful to users everywhere.

  I also hope that making this program freeware will show people how much
I (and others) appreciate what shareware, freeware and public domain
authors are giving to the rest of the Amiga community.

  This program is dedicated to all the shareware, freeware and public
domain authors in the Amiga community!

  Although this program is free, taking into account the many hours I've
put into writing Keeper, if you use it often and feel that it's worth it,
I would gladly accept any contributions ($5 CAN or whatever you think it's
worth, hopefully more :-) ). This would encourage me to continue
supporting this program and let me know what people think of it.
(See @{" Contacting The Author " link author})

@endnode

@node overview "Overview"

Overview
========

  Do you have a LOT of magazines? Did you ever think to yourself "Gee, I 
saw an article about that in one of my subscriptions..." and proceeded 
to look for it? Did you ever have a hard time finding that article? If 
you answered "YES" to all these questions, then this program if for you.

  Keeper allows you to keep track of all the articles, reviews and 
miscellaneous columns of each issue of a magazine subscription and to 
find them easily, quickly and effortlessly. Keeper has all these 
features:

-  Allows to keep a database of 50 different subscriptions with over    
   65 000 records in each.

-  Keeps track of how many issues you've received and are how many left
   to come for each subscription.

-  Keeps track of all important information for each article, such as
   the type, page number, issue number, and a description.

-  Fast and easy to use search routine.

-  The possibility to flag records for later reference.

-  An easy to use WorkBench-style intuition interface.

-  @{" AmigaGuide " link requirements}-style online help

@endnode

@node requirements "Requirements"

Requirements
============

  The requirements for this program is any Amiga computer with a minimum 
of 512k Ram and KickStart 2.04 or higher. A hard drive is recommended 
but not necessary.

  In order to have online help available, you must also have the program
"AmigaGuide" available in the "SYS:Utilities/" directory.

@endnode

@node install "Installation"

Installation
============

  To install Keeper, simply choose the directory you which it to reside
and move "Keeper", its icon and "Keeper.guide" in that directory.

  Keeper assumes that "Keeper.guide" is in the same directory as the
program itself when online help is used, so it MUST reside in the same
directory as Keeper.

@endnode

@node general "General Operation"

Operation
=========

  A note while using the program. At several places in the program there 
will be double outlined string boxes in which information is entered. 
When none these boxes are activated (there is no cursor in any of them), 
you can activate one by usually pressing the first letter (upper or 
lower case) of its name; the same holds true for other gadgets. Also 
note that when information is entered for one string gadget, the program 
will activate the next string gadget so that you can continue entering 
data. All hotkeys will be indicated beside the title of each function
in this document.

  String boxes used to enter information are all double outlined, however, 
you will notice that some string boxes are single outlined. These only 
display information and cannot be edited.

  While entering text, you can press the shifted left and right arrow to
jump to the beginning or the end of the line of text. You can also press
Right-Amiga and X to clear any text entered in the gadget.

  Once data has been entered and saved, you may go back and change it at
any time. The computer will automatically save any changes you've made.

  Keeper has online help available. If you need help with any of the
gadgets or windows in the program, just position the mouse over it and
press the "Help" key on the keyboard. An AmigaGuide style help utility
will be loaded with help information displayed at the top of the window.

  If for any reason online help is unavailable (see @{" Requirements " link requirements} and
@{" Installation " link install}), a low bell will sound meaning that the program cannot
provide you online help.

@endnode

@node use "Using Keeper"

Running
=======

  Start the program by double-clicking on its icon from WorkBench, or by
entering "Keeper" in the shell from the same directory as the program.

  Upon running Keeper, the program will look for a directory called 
"KEEPERDATA" in its root directory. If it is unable to find it, a file 
selector will appear requesting you to double click on the "KEEPERDATA" 
directory. If it is the first time the program is run, you can do one of 
two things:

-  click on OK. This will create a "KEEPERDATA" directory in the root 
   directory of the program.

-  select another directory where you want the "KEEPERDATA" directory 
   to be created, and clicking on OK.

  The next time the program is run, it will automatically detect the 
"KEEPERDATA" directory if you used the first method, or will ask you to 
double click on the directory name in the directory you selected using 
the second method.

  When the program knows where the directory is, it will display the
main screen, which consists of:

-  The subscriptions window. This is where all the subscription names are
   displayed and selected.

-  The close gadget in the upper left corner of the screen. Clicking on
   it will exit the program.

-  The screen toggle gadget in the upper right corner of the screen.
   Clicking it will switch to the WorkBench screen. (NOTE: Since this
   program is written in AMOS, in order to get back to the Keeper
   screen you must press the Left-Amiga and "A" keys together.)

-  The Keeper title icon in the centre at the top of the screen.  
   Clicking it will bring up information about the program.

-  The @{" ADD " link add} gadget. This will let you create a new subscription.

-  The @{" DELETE " link delete} gadget. This will let you delete a subscription.

-  The scroll bar at the right edge of the centre window. This allows
   you to scroll through the list of subscription if there are too many to
   list.












@endnode

@node add "Adding A Subscription"

ADD
===

  This gadget is used to enter a new subscription in the database.

  Upon clicking this gadget, a window will appear containing several 
string gadgets:

    Name: Hotkey = 'N'

  In this gadget you enter the subscription name, for example, "Amiga 
World". The maximum number of characters is 26 and spaces are allowed.

    From: Hotkey = 'F'

  In this gadget you enter information about the start date of the
subscription. For example, suppose your 1 year subscription started from 
the November 1993 issue, you would enter "November 1993" in this gadget. 
30 characters maximum are allowed.

    To: Hotkey = 'T'

  In this gadget you enter the ending date of the subscription. In the 
example above, you would enter "November 1994". 30 characters maximum 
are allowed.

    Comment: Hotkey = 'C'

  In this gadget you enter general information about the subscription such 
as the cost, time for renewal, etc... 80 characters maximum are allowed.

    Total: Hotkey = 'L'

  In this gadget you enter the total number of issues to be received for 
the subscription. Below is another gadget called "Left" which will be 
updated with the "Total" gadget to the same number. 2 characters maximum 
are allowed.

  Two more gadgets are at the bottom of the window:

    Ok: Hotkey = 'O'

  Confirms the information and creates a new subscription record, then 
returns to the main screen and displays the new subscription in the
subscriptions window.

    Cancel: Hotkey = 'A'

  Cancels all the information entered and returns to the main screen.






@endnode

@node delete "Delete Subscription"

DELETE
======

  This will let you delete a selected subscription name. A window will
appear asking you if you really want to delete it.

    OK: Hotkey = 'O'

  Confirms that you want to delete the subscription.

    Cancel: Hotkey = 'C'

  Aborts the deletion process.

@endnode

@node status "Subscription Status Window"

Viewing status of subscription
==============================

  To view the status of the subscription, double click with the right 
mouse button on the subscription name. A window will appear displaying 
the following information: @{" Name " link add 9} of the subscription,@{" From " link add 14} and @{" To "link add 21}
dates, @{" Comment " link add 26}, @{" Total " link add 31} issues and issues Left. These hold the
information you entered when creating the subscription record and can
be edited in the same manner.

  Two more gadgets appear at the bottom of the window:

    OK: Hotkey = 'O'

  This saves any changes you have made and returns to the main screen.

    Update: Hotkey = 'U'

  This allow you to keep track of how many issues are left to be received. 
You would use this every time you'd receive an issue. Clicking this 
gadget decreases the number in the "Left:" string gadget by one. This
lets you know later how many issues are left to come. If you've made a 
mistake (decreased one too many) simply click on the "Total:" string 
gadget and press Return. This will reset the "Left:" gadget to the total
number of issues, then re-adjust the number of issues left by clicking on
"Update".





@endnode

@node enter "Entering Data"

Entering data for a subscription
================================

  Now that we've got things all set up, we can start entering the main 
data. Entering this data will be a long process, but it will save you a 
lot of trouble searching for those article through all those magazines!

  Double clicking with the left mouse button on the subscription name will 
open the record entry window. Displayed on this window is:

    Title: Hotkey = 'T'

  This string gadget is used to enter the name of the article. The maximum 
number of characters allowed is 40.

    Desc.: Hotkey = 'D'

  This string gadget is used to hold a description of the contents of the 
article. The maximum number of characters allowed is 80.

    Issue: Hotkey = 'I'

  This string gadget is used to hold the name/number of the issue in which 
the article is. The maximum number of characters allowed is 30.

    Page: Hotkey = 'P'

  This string gadget holds the page number of the article. 3 characters 
maximum are allowed.


  To the left of these string gadgets are the type gadgets:

    Article: Hotkey = 'A'

    Review: Hotkey = 'R'

    Other: Hotkey = 'O'

  These are used to describe the type of the article. Note that only one 
can be selected.


  Below the type gadgets are other gadgets:

    Three arrows: Hotkey = '.'

  This turns on (selected) or off (raised) the @{" continuous mode " link continuous}.

    Left and right arrows: Hotkeys = left and right cursor keys

  These allow you to list through the records.


  Four more gadgets are along the bottom of the window. We will explore 
these in turn:

     @{" New " link new}       @{" Search " link search}       @{" Tag " link tag}       @{" Menu " link menu}






@endnode

@node new "New"
@next search

   New: Hotkey = 'N'

  This is used to start a new record. When there are no records at all, 
this must be pressed first before anything else can be done. All the 
gadgets in the window will reset and the "Record" string gadget will up 
updated. You can now enter a record.

  After pressing the "New" gadget, the @{" Title " link enter 11} string gadget will be
activated. You can enter the information needed for all the string
gadgets, the computer will automatically cycle through them.

  Next, you will need to select a type for the record, either @{" Article " link enter 34},
@{" Review " link enter 36} or @{" Other " link enter 38}. (Note: In order to make things easier, you can also
you can select the type by pressing Left-Amiga and either the "A", "R" or
"O" keys respectively, but ONLY while a string gadget is activated.)

  In order for a record to be accepted, you must at least have a type 
selected and a title for the record, otherwise the computer will warn 
you if either of these is missing with a bell sound and will wait for the
record to be complete before continuing with other records. All other
string gadgets may be empty.

 @{" Tips on entering records " link tips}

@endnode

@node continuous "Continuous Mode"
@prev enter
@next search

Continuous mode
===============

  If the continuous mode is on, after the "Page" string gadget has been 
edited, and provided the record has a type selected and a title, the 
computer will automatically create a new record. This has the same 
effect as using the @{" New " link new} gadget. This is provided so that you can enter
a series of records without having to use the mouse.

  If the continuous mode is off, you will have to use the @{" New " link new} gadget in
order to create a new record.

@endnode

@node tips "Tips On Entering Records"
@prev enter
@next search

Tips on entering records
========================

  Since entering records can be a long job, especially if you have a lot 
of old magazines, here are some tips that can help the make the job 
easier:

-  When entering descriptions, you should enter keyword about the
   article. For example: you could use the words "printer", "laser",    
   and "inkjet" for an article that talks about different kind of    
   printers.

-  Always be sure to enter important information for later     
   reference, such as the page number or the issue number. This will    
   save a lot of time looking for the article (and it's the point of
   using this program!)

-  For articles that have multiple subjects, such as the "Help Key" in
   Amiga World, you could describe a few of them in one record, and
   describe the rest in another one.

-  Please note that each subscription has a maximum of 65530 records.
   This should be enough for about 2000 (!) magazines.

@endnode

@node search "Searching"
@prev new

Searching
=========

  To the right of the @{" New " link new} gadget is the "Search" gadget:

    Search: Hotkey = 'S'

  Searching through records will allow you to find the article you're 
looking for easily and effortlessly. Once selected, a search string 
gadget window will appear in which you enter the search pattern. Two 
special characters can be used in the search pattern:

    &: this will allow you to do an AND search

    |: this will allow you to do an OR search.

  Note that only one of these can be used in any search string. The 
computer will ignore anything following the second one. The search 
routine is not case sensitive and no quotes are needed.

  Here are some examples of search patterns:

    Amiga & 3000 : This will find any record containing both 'Amiga'
                   and '3000'.

    Amiga | CDTV : This will find any record containing either
                   'Amiga' or 'CDTV'.

    Computer    :  This will find any record containing 'Computer'.

  Once the search pattern has been entered, the window will disappear and 
you will see the record entry window. Note that the "Search" gadget will 
be selected. This indicates that the search mode is on, as there are 
several differences between it and the record entry mode.

  Most of the gadgets react differently in the search mode:

  You can select any of the type gadgets, even more than one. This will 
indicate which records will be searched. Selecting the "Review" type will
only search in records that have that type, while selecting both 
"Review" and "Article" will search in records of either type. Leaving 
all types unselected will have the same effect as selecting all of them.

  The arrow gadgets are now used to indicate the way the search goes; from 
the current record on (right), or from the current record backwards (left).
As the computer is searching through the records, it will display in the 
"Record" string gadget which record it is currently searching.

  The "New" gadget is used to enter a new search pattern. The search 
string gadget window will appear with the current search pattern, which
you can re-edit.

  When the computer has found a record matching the search pattern, it 
will display the record in the window. You can resume the search 
afterwards by selecting either of the arrow gadgets.

  While the computer is searching through the records, you can press the 
right mouse button to abort the search. The computer will display the 
record it was searching when the search was aborted.

  Pressing the "Search" gadget will return to the record entry mode.

@endnode

@node tag "Tag"

Tag
===

    Tag: Hotkey = 'G'

  This will allow you to flag any record for later reference. It can be 
used in both entry and search modes. All tags remain until a different
subscription is selected.

  While in record entry mode, pressing the Shift key while using the arrow 
gadgets will display the next (right gadget) or the previous (left 
gadget) tagged record in the window.

@endnode

@node menu "Menu"

Menu
====

    Menu: Hotkey = 'M'

  This will return you to the main screen. It can be used in both modes.

  NOTE: You should always return to the main screen before turning off
the computer if you won't bother quitting the program. If you do not do 
this, you may lose the records you entered during the session.

@endnode

